{"/service/ndnp/ohi/batch_ohi_bellatrix_ver03/data/sn89075140/00516993315/1937120201/0489.xml":{"full_text":"1937 Christmas Shopping Rush Begins\nWith Bright Promise of Record Sales\nvyun more money lo spend\nthan they have bad In sev\neral years, America's Christmas\nshoppers have started the annual\nbuying rush, bringing to busi\nness the bright promise of sale*\nexceeding the record-breaking\ntotals of last year\nEarly buying has been brisk\nretailers ovei the country have\nreported, although the actua!\nholiday invasion of the stores is\nnot expected to reach Its stride\nuntil mid-December With 21\nshopping days in December mer\nchants anticipate the heaviest\nrush during Christmas week\nPurchasing trends point U\nconservative buying of useful\narticles, as was the case last\nyear, although luxuries will not\nbe neglected. Household fur\nnishings clothing, sports good.\nand automobile accessories hold\nthe spotlight, but expensive\nliquors, perfumes and novelties\nhave not been forgotten.\n\nWfELL-STOCKED stores awa.i\nthe buyers, and the shortage\nwhich confronted late purchas\ners in 1936 are not likely to be\nrepeated Since late summer\nincreasingly heavy express and\ntransport shipments have indi\ncated retailers have been re\nolenishlng depleted stocks.\nAlmost any gift at a wide\nrange of prices is available to\nthe careful shopper. Lingerie\ncosmetics, Jewelry and clothing\ntop the lists for women\u2019s gifts,\nwith ties, clothing and acces\nsories, sports equipment and mo\ntoring aids for men.\nV- Ultra-modern are the toys that\nwill surround the 1937 Christ\nmas tree. Streamlining is pre\ndominant in all wheel toys, me\nchanical trains, and airplanes.\nSeml-scientiflc toys are featured\nrevealing the mysteries of radio,\nelectro-chemistry and engineer\ning.\nDolls that eat and cry in an\n,tv' amazingly human manner pro\nvide the young \u201cmothers\" with an\nsarly opportunity to study child\ncare. Doll houses have gone\nmodernistic, as have doll car\nriages.\nDespite rumblings of war\nthroughout the world, military\ntoys have lost popularity and\nfewer tanks and guns are. being\nBustling shoppers, crowded stores, such as the one pictured\nabove, and jingling cash registers mark the return of the Christ\nmas buying season.\nsold. Musical toys approach a\nperfection comparable with that\nof the real instruments.\n\nf^HRISTMAS card sales have\nincreased, and postal author!*\nties are prepared for a deluge\nof mail greater than that of\n1936. Already long lines have\nbeen forming before postofflce\nwindows, and shipments to for*\neign countries have hit an up\nward surge.\nIssuing the usual \u201cMail Early\u201d\npleas, postmasters cited delayed\ndeliveries of a year ago, in an\neffort to avoid the last-minute\nlam.\nTransportation facilities will\nbe extended from the middle of\nthe month until after tiew Year\u2019s\nas thousands trek homeward for\nthe holidays. Extra trains and\nbuses will be put into service\nand additional flights are planned\nby major airlines.\nThe poor, the sick and the\naged will not be forgotten.\nCharitable agencies report ready\nresponse to appeals for funds\nand welfare authorities hoped\nthat the demands would not ap\nproach the peaks of depression\nyears.\nEven in the face of a business\n\u201crecession,\" Christmas, 1937, ap\nparently will be one of the na\ntion\u2019s merriest.\nColleges Produce Good Grid, Baseball\nTalent for Pros but Fail in Hockey\nBY IRVING UIX\nA MER1CAN colleges and uni\nversities. although they fur\nnish the best material In the\nworld for professional football,\nand a lot of high-class talent for\nbig league baseball, fall short ol\n'producing anything even remote\nly resembling big-time hockey\nmaterial (or National League\nclubs.\nAnd the authority for this\nclaim is none other than Lester\nPatrick, manager of the New\nYork Rangers, who more than\nany other man connected with\nthe ice sport is best qualified to\nspeak on the subject.\nIt's Patrick's contention that a\ncollege coach can take a big 200\npounder and within six weeks\nteach him enough football to\nturn out a pretty good tackle or\nguard\u2014perhaps even an All\nAmerica.\nA smart baseball manager can\ndo pretty much the same with a\nboy, except it\u2019s apt to take a lit\ntle more time.\n\nv\n\n\ni'M,- t:\n\nZ\nK\u2018-\n11 r,\nf\n'0 V.\n.Vi\nDUT not so in hockey. A good\nhockey player has to be a\nreal skater. And in order to\nskate you\u2019ve got to have a lot\nof ice\u2014for as long as four or five\nmonths in the year,\np It takes years to learn to skate\nwell enough to have possibilities\nas a hockey placer.\nSchoolboys in most sections of\nCanada don\u2019t play marbles or\nbaseball. They get out on their\nponds and streams, and .Ice\nskate. As a result Canada pro\nduces the finest hockey players\nin. the world., Practically all ma\njor league stars of 4ny magni\ntude were either Canada born or\ntired. The Rangers, for exam\npie, are a 100 per cent Canadian\noutfit\nCollege hockey In the United\nttatea.tg centered,for the most\npart in the east where Harvard,\nYale, Dartmouth, Brown and\npother* have pretty fair dubs.\n\nBut they\u2019re Just pretty fair.\nOnly one man ever has come\noff a collegiate rink to make the\ngrade in pro ranks. That was\nGeorge Owen, the former Har\nvard star, who went to the Bos\nton Bruins.\nOwen, who also achieved tame\nGeorge Owen, left, former\nHarvard and Boston Bruin\nstar, was the only collegian\never to carve a spectacular\ncareer In big-time hockey, ac\ncording to Lester Patrick,\nabove, manager of the New\nYork Rangers.\nas a Crimson halfback, was a\nnatural. He\u2019d been skating ever\nsince he was 10 years old.\n\nr IVOR can you really learn to\nskate on indoor rinks. The\nbest skaters, according to Pat\nrick, come from the smaller\ntowns in the wide open spaces\nof northern United States, where\nthe kids have access to plenty\nof ice throughout the winter\nThere\u2019s a gleam of hope, how\never, for collegiate hockey. Min\nnesota and Wisconsin are pro\ngressing steadily and other\nschools in the northwest also\nshow signs of breeding some pro\nfessional material.\nIt\u2019s a hopeful doubt that Les\nter Patrick entertains for colle\ngiate hockey. It has' S chance,\nhe admits, but he insists it\u2019ll be\nmany a season before the col\nlege boys send another George\nOwen up into professional cir\ncles.\nlit t nix\n5. A.\ni;,\nSi\n'f-VH1\nCL a S E\nWc Hav* Scvaral\n1937 PONTIACS\n,rn\u2018 Which Carry New Car\nGuarantee*\n^tKtt $250 to $400\nfi\". OHIO'S OLDEST\nPONTIAC DEALER\n_ IWmrl? at Crjihl Coraw\nB im\u00bbwm Toledo,\u00ab.\nin\u2014i ant\n_^-.as*JLi.4cd\u2018lA'At.\nii J\nFOR BEST\nWRAPPING RESULTS\nBUURS USE\nBROTHER NOAH\nSERVICE KRAFT\nDvrabl* Brown 90 Gray Kraft\nZEBRA DRUG BOND\nTUB\nToledo Merduudise Co.\nKODAKS\nKODAK JR. Series 2\u2014\nAnastigmai Lena _$ US\nKODAK JR.\u2014Bimat Lens 1L75\nKODAK JR.\u2014P 6.3 Lens.. 1L5*\nBROWNIES as low as\u2014 l.M\nGross Special\u2014F 4.5 Lens 15.95\nCandid Camera F4.5 Lens 12L50\nEVERYTHING PHOTOGRAPHIC\nfcput FinUhin# a Specialty\nGross Photo Sopply Co.\n04 MaSlca An. 1* Spttaw Am*\nTOLEDO, OHIO\nRecently passing the picket line\nof a local business establishment a\nfriend heard an observer comment:\n\"There goes the Mardh of \u2018lost\u2019\nTime!\u2019*\nQ. \u201cWho invented the jig-saw\npuzzle?\u201d\nA. \u201cA butcher who droped a 5\ndollar bill by mistake into a meat\nchopping machine.\u201d\n4& MONEY\nIf you want to Refinance your Farm\nat a lower rate of interest or make a\nnew mortgage we can handle choice\nFarm Loans as low as 4% per cent.\nCOWAN REAL ESTATE\n5521 Douglas Rd.. Toledo, 0.\nDR. S. L. BROWN, O.D.\nDR. JDS. R. ALLAN, O.D.\nOptomeric Eyesight Specialists\nQUEEN OPTICAL CO.\n436-4S7 Spitzer Bldg. 4th Floor\nTOLEDO, OHIO\nKELLER-NASH\nGUARANTEED\nUSED CARS AT\nWHOLESALE PRICES\nWe have moved to a new location at Madison and 11th\nwhere we have a fine selection of used cars inside out\nof